x4codes.hlp: University of California, Los Angeles, CA, United States of America

x4freetext: The Samples, 0.6-1.1 Mg/Cm**2 Thick, About 2*2 Inch
Area, were Prepared by Either Painting or Evaporation
Onto 0.001-Inch Aluminum Foil.
- By Compiler - No Details Given For Purity of the
Samples.
The Full-Energy Proton Beam
Had Energy Spread Less Than 1%. Beryllium Absobers
Were Used to Reduce the Energy of the Beam. The Energy
Of the Beam Passing the Fission Chamber was Measured
With the Use of Additional Copper Absorbers and
Ionization Chambers.
A Cancellation-Type Ionization Chamber of 2-Pi
Geometry, Filled with 1 Atmosphere of Hydrogen Gas,
Consisted of Three Electrodes, Arranged So As to Form
Two Adjacent Parallel-Plate Ionization Chambers. A
Beam of Charged Particles Passing Through the Fission
Chamber Produced Almost Equal Amounts of Ionization in
Both these Regions. Almost Complete Cancellation of
The Pulses Caused by the Beam Ionization Could be
Obtained. The Beam was Monitored by an Additional
Parallel-Plate Ionization Chamber Filled with 1
Atmosphere of Argon. See Rel-Ref For Details of the
Beam Monitoring.
Performed: Background Pulses Due to Incomplete
Cancellation of Proton-Induced Ionization: Less Than
1% For Uranium-238, Uranium-235 and Thorium-232; Less
Than 10% For Bismuth, and Less Than 25% For Gold.
Sample-Thickness Corrections, 8-14%, Determined in
Special Measurements with Thinner Samples at 336 MeV.
Deviation of the Effective Solid Angle from 2-Pi,
The Neutron Contamination of the Beam, 2% For Uranium-
235, 1% For the Other Target Nuclei.
Negligible: the Loss of Fission Events Due to Pile-Up
Of Fission Pulses, Less Than 1%.
Uncertainty in Determination of Sample
Thickness.
Uniformity of Sample Material.
Self-Absorption of Fission Fragments in the
Sample Material.
Extrapolation to Zero Bias.
Momentum Transfer to the Target Nucleus.
Uncertainty Due to Determination of Beam
Energy.
Calibration of Beam Monitor.
Geometry of the Chamber.
Total Systematic Error Given by Authors, As a
Result of All Above Mentioned Contributions.
The Uncertainties Shown in the Figures and
Given in the Data Sections are Purely Due to Counting
Statistics.
